<div id="review_2490762354" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2490762354" />
    <a title="Jayme" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11345366-jayme"><img alt="Jayme" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545654456p2/11345366.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2490762354?book_show_action=true">Nov 25, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jayme" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jayme" href="/user/show/11345366-jayme">Jayme</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2490762354" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer689007958940572177">1950: Idlewild Hall, is still open, despite the rumors that it is haunted, by a girl called Mary Hand. <br/><br/>“Don’t let her in!” <br/><br/>Girls with nowhere else to go attend the school, passing down the story of Mary Hand to the next class, by writing about their sightings in the margins, of the textbook, “Latin Grammar for Girls”, which is used every semester...<br/><br/>“Mary Hand wears a black dress and veil. She laughed like my dead little brother. Madeleine Grazer, February 2, 1935”:<br/><br/>The latest roommates and friend</span>
  <span id="freeText689007958940572177" style="display:none">1950: Idlewild Hall, is still open, despite the rumors that it is haunted, by a girl called Mary Hand. <br /><br />“Don’t let her in!” <br /><br />Girls with nowhere else to go attend the school, passing down the story of Mary Hand to the next class, by writing about their sightings in the margins, of the textbook, “Latin Grammar for Girls”, which is used every semester...<br /><br />“Mary Hand wears a black dress and veil. She laughed like my dead little brother. Madeleine Grazer, February 2, 1935”:<br /><br />The latest roommates and friends using the textbooks are Katie, Roberta, CeCe and Sonia, till one of them disappears....<br /><br /><br /><br />Vermont 2014: Idlewild Hall sits in disrepair, having been closed for years. It’s garden is where Mary Hand is still spotted on occasion. It’s crumbling school the one a student disappeared from in 1950, and its grounds were the final resting place for a murdered girl’s body twenty years ago..<br /><br />The body found was that of journalist Fiona Sheridan’s older sister. <br /><br />So when Fiona learns that an anonymous donor wants to reopen the school, Fiona decides to do a story about it. But as she is touring the grounds during the initial renovations, a discovery is made, which will change the focus of the article. <br /><br />A discovery that will tie the past and present together in ways you cannot imagine. <br /><br />The narratives alternate between the past and present but are easy to follow.<br /><br />When I first began reading this, I was thinking that I enjoyed the way the author was able to create a mood, and set the scene, but would this book really be any different from the many, many books out there, with a “student narrative” (usually boring to me) where you learn about the students’ secrets...and an “adult” narrative, where the secrets get exposed??<br /><br />Well, let me assure you...the “students” narrative definitely took a turn I could’ve never predicted and it was not only surprising but also enlightening.<br /><br />Be sure to read the epilogue"......the fact that some of what you’ll read about actually occurred is “haunting” in itself...</span>
  <a data-text-id="689007958940572177" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


