<div id="review_2229582643" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2229582643" />
    <a title="Tammy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50603889-tammy"><img alt="Tammy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1566220700p2/50603889.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2229582643?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tammy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tammy" href="/user/show/50603889-tammy">Tammy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2229582643" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1146335840619826507">I’m weary of thrillers. I’m not a fan of ghost stories. And, bad girls in boarding school has been done to death. Sounds like a recipe for a disappointing read but Broken Girls was a pleasant surprise. The four “bad” girls in 1950 weren’t bad by today’s standards, in fact they weren’t bad at all. Mostly, these girls were shuttled off to a crumbling and severe boarding school to shield their parents from embarrassment and then a student goes missing. Everyone was afraid at Idlewild Hall even the </span>
  <span id="freeText1146335840619826507" style="display:none">I’m weary of thrillers. I’m not a fan of ghost stories. And, bad girls in boarding school has been done to death. Sounds like a recipe for a disappointing read but Broken Girls was a pleasant surprise. The four “bad” girls in 1950 weren’t bad by today’s standards, in fact they weren’t bad at all. Mostly, these girls were shuttled off to a crumbling and severe boarding school to shield their parents from embarrassment and then a student goes missing. Everyone was afraid at Idlewild Hall even the teachers but why and of what? <br /><br />The first few chapters truly made me uneasy and I was grateful to enter 2014 where a journalist is beginning to delve into the reconstruction of dilapidated Idlewild Hall which happens to be the location of her sister’s murder in 1994. Is the man in prison for her murder really the murderer? And exactly what happened to the missing girl in 1950? The answers may surprise you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1146335840619826507" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


